<br>
(1) You're going to have to choose to make some of your abilities stronger than others.<br>
<br>
(2) The strongest they can be is equal to your level, HOWEVER, all classes are set up and balanced to be right with specializations at 2/3 your level.  The extra 1/3 you could get is there so people can get super strong in something if they want to.  <br>
<br>
(3) Since the points you get increase every level, it's fairly easy to correct mistakes in your lower levels.<br>
<br>
(4) For the points it would cost you to spec one line to your level, you can spec TWO lines to 2/3.  (I know it sounds crazy, but I checked it).<br>
<br>
(5) So for an eldritch, you have 3 lines to choose from, and enough points to spec ONE to level.  That'll make you very one-sided.  A better approach is 2 lines to 2/3 (which will get you to a good point in both lines).<br>
<br>
(6) Note that the spell lists are still being added to, by the way.<br>
<br>
(7) If you rather like all 3 lines, you can take the points for one of the 2/3 lines and split it between the other two and spec them to 1/2 (also not bad).  You'd be good in a lot of different situations (solo, group, rvr, etc.).  That's the theory.<br>
<br>
I'll summarize:  <br>
<br>
Eldritch could go Mana 1 Light 0 Void 0 or something like that, which would leave you with only the base spells in the two you didn't spec;<br>
<br>
Or Mana 2/3 Light 2/3 Void 0, two balanced lines with only base spells in the last, or<br>
<br>
Mana 2/3 Light 1/2 Void 1/2, or some variation on that.<br>
<br>
Email me if this still makes no sense.<br>
<br>
Sentry <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub30.ezboard.com/ucorellionseladrine.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Corellion Seladrine</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#333333>(10/19/01 5:33:58 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: DAoC players might want to read this. =) (&lt;-- Xiltin </span><hr size=1> Aye, this is true Sentry. However, if you do more than one as a caster, you are screwed. That is all there is to it.<br>
<br>
Yeah, you can get 2 different lines up to 2/3 SKILL LEVEL, but that does not necessarily mean the spells you have from that level are 2/3 your max. Which, for example an Eldritch, means that at level 50 with 2 lines specialized, you will have 35 skill points in each one. This will leave you at level 50 with 2 lines of specializations, where your highest spells from both specializations are just barely level 30 or a bit higher spells.<br>
<br>
Which in turn, means that the spell isn't going to do jack to any level 40+ mob, or player character. Even if you did manage to get the spell to land, it would do little, if any at all damage or effect.<br>
<br>
You have to specialize in one line if you are in it for the long game. Even if you are not, yeah at level 50, both lines will be in the 30's level, but up until level 50, you will constantly be LEVELS behind in spells and will suck in groups, and MAJORLY in rvr/pvp.<br>
<br>
So, even though you would still be fine, because all of your base spells level up automatically ( you wouldn't be useless), it's just that your specialized spells (where the effects and damage really show) will be of little to no use. So, I guess you wouldn't be all the way screwed, but technically you would be.<br>
<br>
In my opinion, it's still one specialization all the way. At least for an Eldritch, and any caster for that matter.<br>
<br>
Also, the only lines you get &quot;base&quot; spell upgrades automatically are the ones you start with. Eldritches get automatic upgrades to their base lines - Sun, Moon, and Eclipse - you get no &quot;base&quot; spells in specialization at all. Meaning, if you don't put any points in it, there are no spells. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub30.ezboard.com/ucorellionseladrine.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Corellion Seladrine</A> at: 10/20/01 8:00:29 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub30.ezboard.com/ugermish.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Germish</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://i1.yimg.com/1/1fa/tn_1e.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sentinent Wanderer</span><br>  Posts: 212<br> <font color=#333333>(10/21/01 6:57:32 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://i1.yimg.com/1/1fa/tn_34.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: DAoC players might want to read this. =) (&lt;-- Xiltin </span><hr size=1> Sorry Gnome Boy, I got to take Sent's side on this one (well .... for the most part).  I feel most spell classes should move points around to different areas because you get &quot;free&quot; lines of spells that go up even if you put no point into them.  <br>
<br>
But Gnome boy has a point about the Eldritches I feel.  They should pick one and stick to it.  An Eldritches number one job seems to be destorying a target fast and as messy as they can (body parts going everywhere) and they can do that best by picking one and sticking to it.<br>
